                         ACCOUNT :: An Accounting Program
                         ================================
 
                               September 2nd, 1987
 
 
 
      INTRODUCTION
      ------------
      This BBC Basic accounting program allows you to keep track of, and
      print statements for, a current bank account.
 
 
 
      AUTHOR: Mike Brudenell, University of Newcastle upon Tyne.
      ------
      e-mail: Mike_Brudenell@UK.AC.NCL.MTS
 
 
 
      MACHINE
      -------
      *   BBC Model B (with, or without, a 6502 second processor)
 
      The above is the only machine the Account program has been tested on,
      but it is written in "legal" BBC Basic, and so should also work on:
 
      *   The Electron
      *   The BBC B+ series
      *   The Master 128 series (with, or without, Turbo)
      *   The Archimedes machines
 
 
 
      ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENTS
      -----------------------
      *   At least one disk drive.
 
      *   Basic version 2 (or later).
 
          [ Basic version 1 was only fitted to early BBC B micros.  To find
          out whether your Basic is version 1, simply give the commands:
 
              *BASIC
              REPORT
 
          If the copyright message so displayed is dated 1981, you are using
          Basic version 1, and this program will not work. ]
  
 
      SETTING UP
      ----------
      The program displays a "statement", into which details of your various
      payments can be placed.  Each statement is saved in a separate file.
      If you exceed the maximum number of entries on a statement in any one
      month, you will need to create additional ones.
 
      I tend to use the scheme of naming files "Jan87", "Feb87", etc., with
      (the only occasionally needed) additional files named "Jan87a",
      "Feb87a", etc.  This scheme allows old files to be easily deleted
      using the filename pattern "*87*".
 
      The program can be set up to operate in one of two modes, "Big Model"
      and "Small Model".  The former gives twenty-seven entries per
      statement (screen), the latter only twenty.  The Big Model is
      obviously better to use but, because of memory requirements, can only
      be used on machines fitted with Shadow screen RAM, or with a 6502
      Second Processor active.
 
          [ Note:- The program has been tested on both a standard
          Model B, and on a 6502 second processor.  As no machine
          with Shadow Memory has been available to me, the code to
          check the amount of memory left may not work properly.
          Please let me know if you have problems ]
 
      The program is initially set up to operate as a Big Model.  If you
      need to change this to the Small Model, simply LIST the first few
      lines of the program.  A comment will tell you what change needs to be
      made.
 
 
 
      COMMANDS
      --------
 
      E (Edit)
          Edit Mode is started.  It is terminated by pressing the Escape
          key.  (See the "Editing" description).
 
      C (Clear)
          The statement is cleared.
 
      Q (Quit)
          Quit leaves the Account program.
 
      P (Print)
          The statement is printed on the printer.
 
      L (Load)
          Loads a statement previously saved to disk.  A check is made that
          the file being loaded is for the current Model (Big/Small).
 
      S (Save)
          Saves the current statement to disk.
 
      T (Terminate)
          Once a file is finished with (ie.  checked against a real Bank
          Statement) it can be "terminated" to prevent further alterations.
          All that Termination involves is locking the file using the
          *ACCESS command, so the process is easily reversed from Basic if
          need be!
 
      ? (Catalog)
          The names of the statements on the current disk are displayed.
          These are kept by the program in the directory "pound" (ie.  the
          pound-sign)
 
      H (Help)
          This displays the single character commands (and nothing else!).
 
 
 
      EDITING
      -------
 
      a)  MOVING AROUND
          -------------
          When in Edit Mode, the cursor can be freely moved using the Arrow
          Keys around the various fields displayed on the screen, with the
          following exceptions:
 
          *   The "Month" and "Initial Balance" fields are reached by going
              Leftwards from the first (top-most) entry's date field.
 
          *   To add a new entry to the balance sheet, move the cursor to
              its date field and set this to a non-zero value.  Only after
              this is done can the cursor be positioned elsewhere on the new
              entry line.
 
 
      b)  ALTERING AN ITEM
          ----------------
          To alter any item, "open" the field by pressing the Copy key.  You
          may then type in a new value.
 
          *   Pressing the Return key finishes the alteration and keeps the
              change,
 
          *   Pressing the Escape key restores its original value.
 
          Every field will only accept certain valid characters (eg. digits
          and "-" for numbers; "X" or " " for the "Chk" fields).
 
 
      c)  ALTERING WHOLE ENTRIES
          ----------------------
          *   New entries can only be added to the end of the balance
              sheet.
 
          *   An entry can be deleted by changing its date field to "0".
 
 
      d)  LEAVING
          -------
          Edit Mode is left by pressing the Escape key.  The "Balance"
          fields and totals are then recalculated.
 
 
      e)  CHECKING YOUR BANK STATEMENT
          ----------------------------
          The "Chk" column enables you to mark off entries as you check them
          against a Bank Statement.  The only characters it accepts are "X"
          and " " (space).
 
          When all entries have been checked off, the file can be terminated
          using the "T" command.

